{"title_page": "Aamaguhan, Chhattisgarh", "text_new": "'''Aamaguhan''' is an Indian [[village]] siuated in the \u201cTehsil Bade Rajpur\u201d of [[District]] \u201cBastar\u201d of the state [[Chhattisgarh]] ([[India]]). It is a medium sized village that falls under the Gram Panchayat of Baijanpuri & BADERAJPUR (Janpad Panchayat) with Kondagaon (Zilla Panchayat).<ref>{{cite web |title=Village &#038; Panchayats District Kondagaon - Government of Chhattisgarh |url=https://kondagaon.gov.in/village-panchayats/ |website=kondagaon.gov.in}}</ref>\n==Government==\nIt falls under the Lok Sabha Constituency of \u201cBastar\u201d which is reserved for Scheduled Tribes (ST) candidates.\n==Population==\nAccording to the Indian Government Census of 2011, it has total 144 families were residing. The population was 658 of which 329 were males while 329 were females. \n\n==Demographic Information ==\nThe Pincode of Aamaguhan is 494347 with post office Bade Rajpur BO.<ref>{{cite web |title=Demographic Information |url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/VAS/Pages/LocatePostOffices.aspx?Pin=cVWjuA2se5M= |website=indiapost.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nNearby Railway Stations : The nearest Railway station is JAGDALPUR JDB.\nNearest Airports are Swami Vivekananda Airport, Raipur, and Chhattisgarh.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aamaguhan Village in Bastar district of Chhattisgarh |url=https://study4sure.com/general-info/villages/chhattisgarh/bastar/village-list.php?village=Aamaguhan |website=study4sure.com}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n\n[[Category:Villages]]\n[[Category:Indian Villages]]\n[[Category:District Bastar Villages]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh Villages]]\n", "text_old": "'''Aamaguhan''' is an Indian [[village]] siuated in the \u201cTehsil Bade Rajpur\u201d of [[District]] \u201cBastar\u201d of the state [[Chhattisgarh]] (India). It is a medium sized village that falls under the Gram Panchayat of Baijanpuri & BADERAJPUR (Janpad Panchayat) with Kondagaon (Zilla Panchayat).<ref>{{cite web |title=Village &#038; Panchayats District Kondagaon - Government of Chhattisgarh |url=https://kondagaon.gov.in/village-panchayats/ |website=kondagaon.gov.in}}</ref>\n==Government==\nIt falls under the Lok Sabha Constituency of \u201cBastar\u201d which is reserved for Scheduled Tribes (ST) candidates.\n==Population==\nAccording to the Indian Government Census of 2011, it has total 144 families were residing. The population was 658 of which 329 were males while 329 were females. \n\n==Demographic Information ==\nThe Pincode of Aamaguhan is 494347 with post office Bade Rajpur BO.<ref>{{cite web |title=Demographic Information |url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/VAS/Pages/LocatePostOffices.aspx?Pin=cVWjuA2se5M= |website=indiapost.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nNearby Railway Stations : The nearest Railway station is JAGDALPUR JDB.\nNearest Airports are Swami Vivekananda Airport, Raipur, and Chhattisgarh.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aamaguhan Village in Bastar district of Chhattisgarh |url=https://study4sure.com/general-info/villages/chhattisgarh/bastar/village-list.php?village=Aamaguhan |website=study4sure.com}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n\n[[Category:Villages]]\n[[Category:Indian Villages]]\n[[Category:District Bastar Villages]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh Villages]]\n", "name_user": "Rajeev Gaur123", "label": "safe", "comment": "internal linking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aamaguhan,_Chhattisgarh"}
{"title_page": "Sergei Karasev", "text_new": "{{Eastern Slavic name|Gennadyevich|Karasev}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name            = Sergei Karasev\n| image           = Sergei Karasev (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Karasev in 2018\n| full_name       = Sergei Gennadyevich Karasev\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1979|6|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| years1          = \n| league1         = [[Russian Premier League]]\n| role1           = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2010\u2013\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Sergei Gennadyevich Karasev''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u0434\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0451\u0432}}; born 12 June 1979) is a [[Russia]]n international [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\nKarasev became a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]] referee in 2010.<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=rus/footballofficials/referees/peoplekind=ref.html \"Russia: Referees\"]. Retrieved on 2 May 2013.</ref> He has refereed at [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]],<ref>[http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=4195&linkType=referee&contextType=bio Profile]</ref> beginning with the Group A match between [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[FYR Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]].<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/europe/matches/round=258374/match=300182204/report.html \"Match Report - Scotland - FYR Macedonia 1:1 (1:1)\"]. 11 September 2012. Retrieved on 2 May 2013.</ref>\n\nKarasev is married with two children. His primary hobby is attending [[Heavy metal music|metal]] concerts. In his interview for [[RIA Novosti]], he names [[Slayer]] as his favourite metal band.<ref>[https://rsport.ria.ru/interview/20160513/921818912.html \"\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0435\u0432: \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u044e\u0442, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u044f \u043b\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0438 \u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043c\u0441 \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0447\"]</ref>\n\n==List of notable matches==\n\n* [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] 1-1 [[Hungary National football team|Hungary]], [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]\n* [[FC Barcelona]] 3-1 [[FC Arsenal]], [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League 2016]]\n* [[FC Barcelona]] 4-0 [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]], [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League 2017]]\n* \n*\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{UEFA Elite Referees}}\n{{UEFA Euro 2016 referees}}\n{{2018 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karasev, Sergei}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 referees]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Football referees at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Russia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Eastern Slavic name|Gennadyevich|Karasev}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| officialname    = Sergei Karasev\n| image           = Sergei Karasev (cropped).jpg\n| fullname        = Sergei Gennadyevich Karasev\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1979|6|12|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| years1          = \n| league1         = [[Russian Premier League]]\n| role1           = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2010\u2013\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}\n'''Sergei Gennadyevich Karasev''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0413\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u0434\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0451\u0432}}; born 12 June 1979) is a [[Russia]]n international [[Referee (association football)|referee]].\n\nKarasev became a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]] referee in 2010.<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=rus/footballofficials/referees/peoplekind=ref.html \"Russia: Referees\"]. Retrieved on 2 May 2013.</ref> He has refereed at [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]],<ref>[http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=4195&linkType=referee&contextType=bio Profile]</ref> beginning with the Group A match between [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[FYR Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]].<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/europe/matches/round=258374/match=300182204/report.html \"Match Report - Scotland - FYR Macedonia 1:1 (1:1)\"]. 11 September 2012. Retrieved on 2 May 2013.</ref>\n\nKarasev is married with two children. His primary hobby is attending [[Heavy metal music|metal]] concerts. In his interview for [[RIA Novosti]], he names [[Slayer]] as his favourite metal band.<ref>[https://rsport.ria.ru/interview/20160513/921818912.html \"\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0435\u0432: \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u044e\u0442, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u044f \u043b\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0438 \u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043c\u0441 \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0447\"]</ref>\n\n==List of notable matches==\n\n* [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] 1-1 [[Hungary National football team|Hungary]], [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]\n* [[FC Barcelona]] 3-1 [[FC Arsenal]], [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League 2016]]\n* [[FC Barcelona]] 4-0 [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]], [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League 2017]]\n* \n*\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{UEFA Elite Referees}}\n{{UEFA Euro 2016 referees}}\n{{2018 FIFA World Cup referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karasev, Sergei}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian football referees]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 referees]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Football referees at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Russia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update infobox to remove article from unknown parameter category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergei_Karasev"}
{"title_page": "Nintendo Land", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title = Nintendo Land\n|image = Nintendo Land box artwork.png\n|alt = \n|caption = North American box art\n|developer = [[Nintendo Entertainment Analysis & Development|Nintendo EAD]]\n|publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n|producer = [[Katsuya Eguchi]]\n|director = Takayuki Shimamura<br/>Yoshikazu Yamashita\n|composer = Ryo Nagamatsu\n|artist=Tsubasa Sakaguchi\n|released = {{Video game release|NA|November 18, 2012|PAL|November 30, 2012|JP|December 8, 2012}}\n|genre = [[Party game#Video games|Party]], [[adventure game|adventure]]\n|platforms = [[Wii U]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Nintendo Land'''''|\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9|Nintend\u014d Rando}} is a [[Party game#Video games|party video game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] as a [[pack-in game|pack-in]] [[launch game|launch title]] for the [[Wii U]] [[home video game console]] in [[2012 in video gaming|2012]]. The game was first announced at [[E3 2012]] during Nintendo's press conference.\n\n''Nintendo Land'' features twelve [[minigame]]s, each based on an existing Nintendo game [[Media franchise|franchise]] such as ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' and ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'', depicted as [[Amusement park#Rides and attractions|attractions]] in the [[eponymous]] fictional [[amusement park]] with an Attraction Tour train designed as a tournament that utilizes all minigames. The minigames are designed to demonstrate the concept of Wii U and its [[Wii U GamePad]] controller to new players, in the same way the 2006 game ''[[Wii Sports]]'' demonstrated the [[Wii]] and its [[Wii Remote]], utilizing many of the controller's features, including its [[touchscreen]] controls and motion-sensing capabilities. Some minigames incorporate the [[Wii Remote Plus]] and [[Wii Remote#Nunchuk|Nunchuk]] controllers for alternate control schemes and [[multiplayer]] support, which also helps exhibit \"[[asymmetric gameplay]]\", a concept in which certain players have different experiences based on the controller they use.\n\n''Nintendo Land'' was mostly liked by critics, and sold 5.19 million copies as of December 2017, making one of the [[List of best-selling Wii U video games|highest-selling Wii U games]] at number five. The ability to download the game was originally removed from the [[Nintendo eShop]] in North America in November 2013,<ref name=\"eShop removal\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/11/nintendo_land_has_been_removed_from_the_north_american_eshop| title= Nintendo Land has been removed from the North American eShop|website= Nintendo Life|date=2013-11-10|accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> but was re-added in August 2016.<ref name=\"eShop return\">{{cite web| url=http://nintendoeverything.com/new-nintendo-selects-dropped-to-20-on-the-eshop-nintendo-land-available-digitally-again/| title= New Nintendo Selects dropped to $20 on the eShop, Nintendo Land available digitally again|publisher= Nintendo Everything|date=2016-08-26|accessdate=2013-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game takes place in an [[amusement park]] setting, which serves as a hub for the thirteen minigames, which are depicted as the park's attractions. A robotic character named Monita guides the player through ''Nintendo Land''{{'}}s features and attractions. The first twelve minigames of ''Nintendo Land'' are based on popular Nintendo franchises (two of the attractions (Metroid Blast and Mario Chase) are based on Wii U tech demos shown at [[E3 2011]], but are modified to feature Nintendo characters) and are designed to incorporate elements which utilize the features of the [[Wii U GamePad]], often in conjunction with other players using [[Wii Remote]]s and Nunchucks (with some games supporting up to five players in this configuration), with the thirteenth being an Attraction Tour train that is depicted as a tournament and uses two to five players.<ref name=metro-nl>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land preview: Zelda: Battle Quest and Luigi's Ghost Mansion|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tech/games/901203-nintendo-land-preview-zelda-battle-quest-and-luigis-ghost-mansion|publisher=Metro|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> The combination of Wii Remotes and Wii U GamePads allows for what Nintendo calls \"asymmetric gameplay,\" where players have different experiences depending on which controller scheme they use.<ref name=morning-sun>{{cite web|title=\u2019NintendoLand,\u2019 \u2018Mario Bros.\u2019 coming to Wii U|url=http://www.themorningsun.com/article/20120609/ENTERTAINMENT01/120609685/-nintendoland--mario-bros--coming-to-wii-u|publisher=The Morning Sun|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref> Completing minigames and completing certain objectives earns coins, which can be used to play a single-player [[pachinko]] minigame. Winning pachinko stages will earn new items for decorating the Nintendo Land hub area.\n\n===Team attractions===\nNumber of players: 1\u20135<ref name=\"n-styles1\">{{cite web|url=http://n-styles.com/main/archives/2012/09/14-011500.php |title=[NS&#93; \u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30c0\u30a4\u30ec\u30af\u30c8\u3067Wii U\u65b0\u4f5c\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u7d39\u4ecb\u3001\u30e2\u30f3\u30cf\u30f3\u6700\u65b0\u4f5c\u767b\u5834\uff01 |publisher=N-styles.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref> (1-4 in ''The Legend of Zelda: Battle Quest'')\n\n;''[[The Legend of Zelda|The Legend of Zelda: Battle Quest]]''\nBased upon ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series. Up to three players (respectively dressed in red, blue, and yellow) use their Wii Remotes as swords to fight AI enemies. One more player (in green) uses the Wii U GamePad to control a character in the rear of the pack using a [[bow and arrow]]. The player with the GamePad can also lift their controller to spy for sniping AI.<ref name=metro-nl/>  To reload their bow and arrow, the player aims the GamePad down.\n\n;''[[Metroid|Metroid Blast]]''\nBased upon the ''[[Metroid]]'' series and the \"Battle Mii\" tech demo from E3 2011. It is an [[action-adventure game]], similar to its original series. The player using the Wii U GamePad controls [[Samus Aran|Samus']] Gunship, while up to four players with Wii Remotes and Nunchuks control Mii characters on foot, wearing Varia Suits. There are three modes, \"Assault Mission\", \"Surface-Air Combat\", and \"Ground Battle\". In \"Assault Mission\", the players cooperate to defeat waves of enemies and complete missions. In \"Surface-Air Combat\", the players with Wii Remotes and Nunchuks try to shoot down the player with the GamePad. In \"Ground Battle\" all players use Wii Remotes and Nunchuks in a battle for tokens.<ref name=IGN-mb>{{cite web|title=gengame-mb|url=http://gengame.net/2012/09/metroid-blast-assault-mission-mode-revealed-plus-ground-v-air-and-free-for-all-modes/|publisher=GenGAME|accessdate=24 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018114730/http://gengame.net/2012/09/metroid-blast-assault-mission-mode-revealed-plus-ground-v-air-and-free-for-all-modes/|archivedate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n;''[[Pikmin (series)|Pikmin Adventure]]''\nBased on the ''[[Pikmin (series)|Pikmin]]'' series. One player controls [[Captain Olimar]] who can command tiny Pikmin using the Wii U GamePad, whilst four additional players (as red, blue, yellow and white Pikmin) can control larger Pikmin using the Wii Remotes. Players must work together to help navigate levels and defeat enemies, including a boss at the end of the stage. When the boss is defeated, the players board Olimar's ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5943133/heres-the-pikmin-mini+game-for-wii-u |title=You Asked For More Pikmin, So Nintendo Is Giving It To You. Twice |publisher=Kotaku.com |date=2012-09-13 |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref> There is also a Versus Mode where the players compete for candy.\n\n===Competitive attractions===\nNumber of players: 2\u20135<ref name=\"n-styles1\"/>\n\n;''[[Super Mario|Mario Chase]]''\n''Mario Chase'', inspired by the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series, is a [[Tag (game)|tag]]-based game that takes place inside an arena consisting of large obstacles, hills, and slides. One player using the GamePad, whose Mii is dressed as [[Mario]], runs away from up to four players, whose Mii characters are dressed in [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]] costumes, whose goal is to pursue and catch the single player. The Mario player, who views the action on the Wii U GamePad screen from a [[top-down perspective]], has a map of the entire arena and can see the location of all the Toad players. The Toad players view the action on the television in [[Split screen (computer graphics)|split-screen]] from a [[Virtual camera system#Third person view games|third person perspective]], and are each only given his current distance from Mario in yards or meters (depending on the region). The Toad player(s) win if one of them catches Mario before the [[Time limit (video gaming)|time limit]] expires, otherwise the Mario player will win. If there are two players, two computer-controlled Yoshi carts will assist the Toad.<ref name=\"nwr review\"/>\n\n;''[[Luigi's Mansion|Luigi's Ghost Mansion]]''\n''Luigi's Ghost Mansion'', inspired by the 2001 [[Nintendo GameCube]] launch title ''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'' and based on the 2003 game ''[[Pac-Man Vs.]]'', is a game in which up to four players (dressed like Mario, [[Luigi]], [[Wario]] and [[Waluigi]]) assume the roles of \"[[ghost]] trackers\" and explore a [[haunted house]] to hunt and capture a ghost, with the ghost being controlled by the player using the GamePad. Each level is set on a different floor with different layouts of rooms and hallways, and the action is [[top-down perspective|viewed from above]], showing the entire floor and the location of all players. The trackers must find the ghost player, who remains invisible on the television screen, and decrease its [[Health (gaming)|health]] (a numerical value from 0 to 100) by shining their flashlights upon it. Meanwhile, the ghost must sneak up and ambush each tracker to make them faint. The ghost's proximity to a tracker is made known when that player's Wii Remote begins to [[Haptic technology#Video games|vibrate]], and different events or conditions may cause the ghost to temporarily become visible to all trackers. Fainted trackers can be revived by the others by using their flashlights, though flashlight energy is in limited reserve and must be restored by picking up battery [[Item (gaming)|items]]. The ghost wins if all the trackers have fainted; the trackers win if they decrease the ghost's health to zero.<ref name=\"nwr review\"/>\n\n;''[[Animal Crossing|Animal Crossing: Sweet Day]]''\nBased on the ''[[Animal Crossing]]'' series, up to four players control animals trying to collect candy as a team before they get caught 3 times by the two guards, with both guards being controlled by the player using the GamePad. As players collect more candies, their movement becomes slower, making it easier for them to be caught.<ref name=metro-nl/><ref name=verge-nl2>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land for Wii U brings mini-games based on Zelda, Donkey Kong to showcase GamePad|url=https://www.theverge.com/gaming/2012/6/5/3065678/nintendo-land-for-wii-u-designed-to-be-the-wii-sports-of-wii-u|website=The Verge|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> If starting the game with only two players, the format changes to the stash rules, where one animal must collect candies and put fifteen into the stashes on the map while avoiding the other player.\n\n;''[[Attraction Tour]]''\n\nA train that features a megamix of all attractions depicted as a tournament. The player chooses how many rounds and how hard the tour will be. At the beginning of the Tour a player chooses who they face, and in what attraction by selecting a card. They must pick from the selected cards by the computer. The cards have who they face, and in what game. Most of the time the computer selects 1-Player attractions, but occasionally it will pick something like a 1-on-1 Mario Chase or The Legend of Zelda: Battle Quest, but in time attack mode. In all games, except for Multiplayer-only attractions, 1 player goes at a time, and the next after that. You will compete for the highest score in that game. In Multiplayer only attractions whoever wins wins. Each player who wins gets 3 points. Between rounds, players who aren't playing (if any) will vote on who they think will win and if they guess correctly they get two points. Whoever gets the most points after all the rounds wins the Attraction Tour.\n\n===Solo attractions===\nNumber of players: 1<ref name=\"n-styles1\"/>\n\n;''[[The Mysterious Murasame Castle|Takamaru's Ninja Castle]]''\nBased on the 1986 [[Famicom Disk System]] game ''[[The Mysterious Murasame Castle]]'', the player uses the [[Wii U GamePad|GamePad]]'s touchscreen to launch paper [[shuriken]] at waves of enemy ninjas. The controller can be tilted in order to change the trajectory of the throws. On boss ninjas or ninjas who are at close range, the players uses a katana.<ref name=verge-nl>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land could be Wii U's system selling new game|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/6/5/3064891/nintendo-land-could-be-wii-us-system-selling-new-game|website=The Verge|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n;''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong's Crash Course]]''\nThe player uses the GamePad's gyroscope abilities to tilt a trolley through a platform-based obstacle course, influenced by the [[Donkey Kong (video game)|original ''Donkey Kong'' arcade game]]. In addition to the tilt input to move the trolley, the player controls the GamePad's two analog sticks, L and R shoulder buttons, and microphone to activate various levers, elevators, and pathways to advance themselves throughout the course.\n\n;''[[F-Zero|Captain Falcon's Twister Race]]''\nA single-player game based on Nintendo's futuristic racing game ''[[F-Zero]]'', where the player must race down a track while avoiding obstacles in 12 different areas.<ref name=ign-fzero>{{cite web|title=E3 2012: The F-Zero Franchise Joins the Nintendo Land Line-Up|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2012/06/06/e3-2012-the-f-zero-franchise-joins-the-nintendo-land-line-up|website=IGN|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> The GamePad is held vertically and its internal gyroscope is used to steer the vehicle when the player rotates the GamePad. The GamePad provides an aerial view (a more strategical view) of the track while the TV provides a third-person view on the track.\n\n;''[[Balloon Fight|Balloon Trip Breeze]]''\nIn this single-player game, based on Nintendo's ''[[Balloon Fight]]'', the player will control their Mii on a play-field similar to the Balloon Trip mode. The player does this by swiping the stylus on the GamePad's touch screen to create gusts of wind that will move the Mii around. The GamePad will offer a zoomed-in view for more precise input whereas the TV will offer a zoomed-out view to see more of the level. The levels are divided into morning, afternoon, evening and night, which are all ended by landing on an island. Occasionally, there are packages on islands that the player can pick up to protect and deliver to the next island.\n\n;''[[List of Yoshi video games|Yoshi's Fruit Cart]]''\nThis attraction is based on the [[List of Yoshi video games|''Yoshi'']] series. The player uses the stylus on the GamePad touchscreen to draw a trail that guides Yoshi to the finish goal of each level while collecting all the fruit in the area. The fruit is only visible on the TV screen, so the player must use reference points in the level's background to draw the path on the GamePad. As the player advances in level, obstacles will appear that take away a life from Yoshi if he is led into one.\n\n;''[[List of Game & Watch games|Octopus Dance]]''\nThis attraction is based on [[List of Game & Watch games|''Game & Watch Octopus'']]. ''Octopus Dance'' is a rhythm game which plays by using the GamePad's Control Sticks and Gyro Sensor. Players must memorize and replicate the actions performed by the instructor on screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/32152 |title=Final Nintendo Land Attractions Explained - News |publisher=Nintendo World Report |date=2012-10-17 |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nDevelopment started shortly after the release of [[Wii Sports Resort]] <ref name=\"Polygoninterview\">{{cite web |last1=Gifford |first1=Kevin |title=Nintendo Land: The postmortem interview |url=https://www.polygon.com/2012/12/12/3757884/nintendo-land-the-postmortem-interview |website=Polygon |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> and was made at a time when the Wii U hadn't been finalized yet which led to the team experimenting with different prototypes. One of said prototypes involved the use of a [[gyroscope]] which directly led to  [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] incorporating the technology into the [[Nintendo 3DS]].<ref name=\"Iwattaasks\">{{cite web |title=Development Started at the Same Time with Wii U |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wiiu/nintendo-land/0/0 |website=Ninteno}}</ref>\n\nThe team's goal was to create a product that showcased all the features the new console could do. This led to a problem, as unlike the similar [[Wii Sports]], the games were not inherently related.<ref name=\"Polygoninterview\"/> Early on one staff member suggested that they attempt to do something that would unite the various Nintendo  franchises. As the team considered this too grand a concept the idea was, at first not taken seriously.<ref name=\"Iwattaasks\"/> The developers initially decided to present the theme as an \"Expo\" which lead to the theme park concept.<ref name=\"Polygoninterview\"/> Although most attractions were easy to theme, the team struggled with some: ''Metroid Blast'' was initially themed around [[Star Fox]], while at one point it was considered to theme ''Donkey Kong Crash Course'' around either [[Excitebike|ExciteBike]] or [[1080\u00b0 Snowboarding|1080 Snowboarding.]].<ref name=\"Polygoninterview\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 78%<ref name=\"gamerankings\"/>\n| MC = 77/100<ref name=\"metacritic\"/>\n| 1UP = B+<ref name=\"1up review\"/>\n| Edge = 7/10<ref name=\"edge review\"/>\n| EuroG = 8/10<ref name=\"eurog review\"/>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"gi review\"/>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"gamerev review\"/>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"gspot review\"/>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"gradar review\"/>\n| IGN = 8.7/10<ref name=\"ign review\"/>\n| NLife = 9/10<ref name=\"nlife review\"/>\n| NWR = 8.5/10<ref name=\"nwr review\"/>\n| ONM = 90%<ref name=\"onm review\"/>\n| Poly = 8/10<ref name=\"poly review\"/>\n}}\n\nThe game has received positive reviews from video games critics, praising its party atmosphere and attractions, especially the way they are developed and built up, with a few being critical of simply showing Wii U GamePad capabilities. [[IGN]] praised the game for showing the Wii U capabilities, its gameplay, its detailed and HD graphics and claiming that \"Wii Sports has met its match\", giving it an 8.7 score.<ref name=\"ign review\"/>\n\n=== Sales ===\nBy March 2014, the game had sold 3.09 million copies,<ref name =\"march 2013 sales\"/> and by December 2014, it had sold 4.44 million units worldwide.<ref name =\"december 2014 sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2015/150129e.pdf|title=Nintendo Earning Release Dec. 2014|publisher=Nintendo|date=2015-01-29|accessdate=2015-01-29}}</ref> {{As of|2018|9|30|df=US}}, the game has sold 5.19 million copies.<ref name=\"nincojp\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"1up review\">{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land Review: Good Fun, But What Does It Mean?|website=[[1UP.com]]|url=http://www.1up.com/reviews/nintendo-land-review-good-fun|accessdate=December 21, 2013|author=Parish, Jeremy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123130824/http://www.1up.com/reviews/nintendo-land-review-good-fun|archivedate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"edge review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.edge-online.com/review/nintendo-land-review/ |title=Nintendo Land review |date=November 16, 2012 |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"eurog review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-15-nintendo-land-review |website=[[Eurogamer]] |author=Welsh, Oil |title=Nintendo Land Review |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |date=November 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gamerankings\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/wii-u/673043-nintendo-land/index.html |title=Nintendo Land for Wii U |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |publisher=[[GameRankings]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gamerev review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendo-land-review/ |title=Nintendo Land Review |date=November 20, 2012 |author=Severino, Anthony |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |publisher=[[Game Revolution]]}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=\"gametrailers review\">{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land Review|publisher=[[GameTrailers]]|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/9dh9tl/nintendo-land-review |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |date=November 18, 2012}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"gi review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/nintendo_land/b/wii_u/archive/2012/11/15/nintendo-land-review.aspx |title=Nintendo Land review |author=Wallace, Kimberley |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |date=November 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gradar review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendo-land-review/ |title=Nintendo Land review |author=Gilbert, Henry |date=November 12, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |publisher=[[GamesRadar]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gspot review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/nintendo-land-review/1900-6400262/ |title=Nintendo Land Review |author=Petit, Carolyn |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ign review\">{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land Review|website=[[IGN]]|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/11/15/nintendo-land-review |date=November 15, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |author=Drake, Audrey}}</ref>\n\n<ref name =\"march 2013 sales\">{{cite web| url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/sales/software/wiiu.html|title= Top Selling Software Sales Units - Wii U Software|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=March 31, 2013|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web | title=Nintendo Land (Wii U)| website=[[Metacritic]] | url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/nintendo-land |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"nincojp\">{{cite web |title=Top Selling Title Sales Units |url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/wiiu.html |publisher=Nintendo}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"nlife review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/wiiu/nintendo_land |title=Nintendo Land (Wii U) Review |author=Sleeper, Morgan |date=November 30, 2012 |website=NintendoLife |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"nwr review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/review/32587 |title=Nintendo Land Review |publisher=Nintendo World Report |date=November 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |author1=Goergen, Andy |author2=Ronaghan, Neal |author3=Barnett, Patrick |author4=Thompson, Scott}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"onm review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/44259/nintendo-land-review/ |title=Nintendo Land review |author=Skrebels, Joe |date=November 27, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |magazine=[[Official Nintendo Magazine]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"poly review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.polygon.com/2012/11/15/3647012/nintendo-land-review-magic-kingdom |title=Nintendo Land Review: Magic Kingdom |author=Plante, Chris |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=November 15, 2013 |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://nintendoland.nintendo.com}}\n\n[[Category:2012 video games]]\n[[Category:Crossover video games]]\n[[Category:Minigame compilations]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Network games]]\n[[Category:Pack-in video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games set in amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Wii U eShop games]]\n[[Category:Wii U games]]\n[[Category:Wii U-only games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Asymmetrical multiplayer video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title = Nintendo Land\n|image = Nintendo Land box artwork.png\n|alt = \n|caption = North American box art\n|developer = [[Nintendo Entertainment Analysis & Development|Nintendo EAD]]\n|publisher = [[Nintendo]]\n|producer = [[Katsuya Eguchi]]\n|director = Takayuki Shimamura<br/>Yoshikazu Yamashita\n|composer = Ryo Nagamatsu\n|artist=Tsubasa Sakaguchi\n|released = {{Video game release|NA|November 18, 2012|PAL|November 30, 2012|JP|December 8, 2012}}\n|genre = [[Party game#Video games|Party]], [[adventure game|adventure]]\n|platforms = [[Wii U]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Nintendo Land'''''|\u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9|Nintend\u014d Rando}} is a [[Party game#Video games|party video game]] developed and published by [[Nintendo]] as a [[pack-in game|pack-in]] [[launch game|launch title]] for the [[Wii U]] [[home video game console]] in [[2012 in video gaming|2012]]. The game was first announced at [[E3 2012]] during Nintendo's press conference.\n\n''Nintendo Land'' features twelve [[minigame]]s, each based on an existing Nintendo game [[Media franchise|franchise]] such as ''[[Mario (franchise)|Mario]]'' and ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'', depicted as [[Amusement park#Rides and attractions|attractions]] in the [[eponymous]] fictional [[amusement park]] with an Attraction Tour train designed as a tournament that utilizes all minigames. The minigames are designed to demonstrate the concept of Wii U and its [[Wii U GamePad]] controller to new players, in the same way the 2006 game ''[[Wii Sports]]'' demonstrated the [[Wii]] and its [[Wii Remote]], utilizing many of the controller's features, including its [[touchscreen]] controls and motion-sensing capabilities. Some minigames incorporate the [[Wii Remote Plus]] and [[Wii Remote#Nunchuk|Nunchuk]] controllers for alternate control schemes and [[multiplayer]] support, which also helps exhibit \"[[asymmetric gameplay]]\", a concept in which certain players have different experiences based on the controller they use.\n\n''Nintendo Land'' was mostly liked by critics, and sold 5.19 million copies as of December 2017, making one of the [[List of best-selling Wii U video games|highest-selling Wii U games]] at number five. The ability to download the game was originally removed from the [[Nintendo eShop]] in North America in November 2013,<ref name=\"eShop removal\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2013/11/nintendo_land_has_been_removed_from_the_north_american_eshop| title= Nintendo Land has been removed from the North American eShop|website= Nintendo Life|date=2013-11-10|accessdate=2013-12-24}}</ref> but was re-added in August 2016.<ref name=\"eShop return\">{{cite web| url=http://nintendoeverything.com/new-nintendo-selects-dropped-to-20-on-the-eshop-nintendo-land-available-digitally-again/| title= New Nintendo Selects dropped to $20 on the eShop, Nintendo Land available digitally again|publisher= Nintendo Everything|date=2016-08-26|accessdate=2013-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game takes place in an [[amusement park]] setting, which serves as a hub for the thirteen minigames, which are depicted as the park's attractions. A robotic character named Monita guides the player through ''Nintendo Land''{{'}}s features and attractions. The first twelve minigames of ''Nintendo Land'' are based on popular Nintendo franchises (two of the attractions (Metroid Blast and Mario Chase) are based on Wii U tech demos shown at [[E3 2011]], but are modified to feature Nintendo characters) and are designed to incorporate elements which utilize the features of the [[Wii U GamePad]], often in conjunction with other players using [[Wii Remote]]s and Nunchucks (with some games supporting up to five players in this configuration), with the thirteenth being an Attraction Tour train that is depicted as a tournament and uses two to five players.<ref name=metro-nl>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land preview: Zelda: Battle Quest and Luigi's Ghost Mansion|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tech/games/901203-nintendo-land-preview-zelda-battle-quest-and-luigis-ghost-mansion|publisher=Metro|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> The combination of Wii Remotes and Wii U GamePads allows for what Nintendo calls \"asymmetric gameplay,\" where players have different experiences depending on which controller scheme they use.<ref name=morning-sun>{{cite web|title=\u2019NintendoLand,\u2019 \u2018Mario Bros.\u2019 coming to Wii U|url=http://www.themorningsun.com/article/20120609/ENTERTAINMENT01/120609685/-nintendoland--mario-bros--coming-to-wii-u|publisher=The Morning Sun|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref> Completing minigames and completing certain objectives earns coins, which can be used to play a single-player [[pachinko]] minigame. Winning pachinko stages will earn new items for decorating the Nintendo Land hub area.\n\n===Team attractions===\nNumber of players: 1\u20135<ref name=\"n-styles1\">{{cite web|url=http://n-styles.com/main/archives/2012/09/14-011500.php |title=[NS&#93; \u30cb\u30f3\u30c6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fc\u30c0\u30a4\u30ec\u30af\u30c8\u3067Wii U\u65b0\u4f5c\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u7d39\u4ecb\u3001\u30e2\u30f3\u30cf\u30f3\u6700\u65b0\u4f5c\u767b\u5834\uff01 |publisher=N-styles.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref> (1-4 in ''The Legend of Zelda: Battle Quest'')\n\n;''[[The Legend of Zelda|The Legend of Zelda: Battle Quest]]''\nBased upon ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series. Up to three players (respectively dressed in red, blue, and yellow) use their Wii Remotes as swords to fight AI enemies. One more player (in green) uses the Wii U GamePad to control a character in the rear of the pack using a [[bow and arrow]]. The player with the GamePad can also lift their controller to spy for sniping AI.<ref name=metro-nl/>  To reload their bow and arrow, the player aims the GamePad down.\n\n;''[[Metroid|Metroid Blast]]''\nBased upon the ''[[Metroid]]'' series and the \"Battle Mii\" tech demo from E3 2011. It is an [[action-adventure game]], similar to its original series. The player using the Wii U GamePad controls [[Samus Aran|Samus']] Gunship, while up to four players with Wii Remotes and Nunchuks control Mii characters on foot, wearing Varia Suits. There are three modes, \"Assault Mission\", \"Surface-Air Combat\", and \"Ground Battle\". In \"Assault Mission\", the players cooperate to defeat waves of enemies and complete missions. In \"Surface-Air Combat\", the players with Wii Remotes and Nunchuks try to shoot down the player with the GamePad. In \"Ground Battle\" all players use Wii Remotes and Nunchuks in a battle for tokens.<ref name=IGN-mb>{{cite web|title=gengame-mb|url=http://gengame.net/2012/09/metroid-blast-assault-mission-mode-revealed-plus-ground-v-air-and-free-for-all-modes/|publisher=GenGAME|accessdate=24 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018114730/http://gengame.net/2012/09/metroid-blast-assault-mission-mode-revealed-plus-ground-v-air-and-free-for-all-modes/|archivedate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n;''[[Pikmin (series)|Pikmin Adventure]]''\nBased on the ''[[Pikmin (series)|Pikmin]]'' series. One player controls [[Captain Olimar]] who can command tiny Pikmin using the Wii U GamePad, whilst four additional players (as red, blue, yellow and white Pikmin) can control larger Pikmin using the Wii Remotes. Players must work together to help navigate levels and defeat enemies, including a boss at the end of the stage. When the boss is defeated, the players board Olimar's ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5943133/heres-the-pikmin-mini+game-for-wii-u |title=You Asked For More Pikmin, So Nintendo Is Giving It To You. Twice |publisher=Kotaku.com |date=2012-09-13 |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref> There is also a Versus Mode where the players compete for candy.\n\n===Competitive attractions===\nNumber of players: 2\u20135<ref name=\"n-styles1\"/>\n\n;''[[Super Mario|Mario Chase]]''\n''Mario Chase'', inspired by the ''[[Super Mario]]'' series, is a [[Tag (game)|tag]]-based game that takes place inside an arena consisting of large obstacles, hills, and slides. One player using the GamePad, whose Mii is dressed as [[Mario]], runs away from up to four players, whose Mii characters are dressed in [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]] costumes, whose goal is to pursue and catch the single player. The Mario player, who views the action on the Wii U GamePad screen from a [[top-down perspective]], has a map of the entire arena and can see the location of all the Toad players. The Toad players view the action on the television in [[Split screen (computer graphics)|split-screen]] from a [[Virtual camera system#Third person view games|third person perspective]], and are each only given his current distance from Mario in yards or meters (depending on the region). The Toad player(s) win if one of them catches Mario before the [[Time limit (video gaming)|time limit]] expires, otherwise the Mario player will win. If there are two players, two computer-controlled Yoshi carts will assist the Toad.<ref name=\"nwr review\"/>\n\n;''[[Luigi's Mansion|Luigi's Ghost Mansion]]''\n''Luigi's Ghost Mansion'', inspired by the 2001 [[Nintendo GameCube]] launch title ''[[Luigi's Mansion]]'' and based on the 2003 game ''[[Pac-Man Vs.]]'', is a game in which up to four players (dressed like Mario, [[Luigi]], [[Wario]] and [[Waluigi]]) assume the roles of \"[[ghost]] trackers\" and explore a [[haunted house]] to hunt and capture a ghost, with the ghost being controlled by the player using the GamePad. Each level is set on a different floor with different layouts of rooms and hallways, and the action is [[top-down perspective|viewed from above]], showing the entire floor and the location of all players. The trackers must find the ghost player, who remains invisible on the television screen, and decrease its [[Health (gaming)|health]] (a numerical value from 0 to 100) by shining their flashlights upon it. Meanwhile, the ghost must sneak up and ambush each tracker to make them faint. The ghost's proximity to a tracker is made known when that player's Wii Remote begins to [[Haptic technology#Video games|vibrate]], and different events or conditions may cause the ghost to temporarily become visible to all trackers. Fainted trackers can be revived by the others by using their flashlights, though flashlight energy is in limited reserve and must be restored by picking up battery [[Item (gaming)|items]]. The ghost wins if all the trackers have fainted; the trackers win if they decrease the ghost's health to zero.<ref name=\"nwr review\"/>\n\n;''[[Animal Crossing|Animal Crossing: Sweet Day]]''\nBased on the ''[[Animal Crossing]]'' series, up to four players control animals trying to collect candy as a team before they get caught 3 times by the two guards, with both guards being controlled by the player using the GamePad. As players collect more candies, their movement becomes slower, making it easier for them to be caught.<ref name=metro-nl/><ref name=verge-nl2>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land for Wii U brings mini-games based on Zelda, Donkey Kong to showcase GamePad|url=https://www.theverge.com/gaming/2012/6/5/3065678/nintendo-land-for-wii-u-designed-to-be-the-wii-sports-of-wii-u|website=The Verge|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> If starting the game with only two players, the format changes to the stash rules, where one animal must collect candies and put fifteen into the stashes on the map while avoiding the other player.\n\n;''[[Attraction Tour]]''\n\nA train that features a megamix of all attractions depicted as a tournament. The player chooses how many rounds and how hard the tour will be. At the beginning of the Tour a player chooses who they face, and in what attraction by selecting a card. They must pick from the selected cards by the computer. The cards have who they face, and in what game. Most of the time the computer selects 1-Player attractions, but occasionally it will pick something like a 1-on-1 Mario Chase or The Legend of Zelda: Battle Quest, but in time attack mode. In all games, except for Multiplayer-only attractions, 1 player goes at a time, and the next after that. You will compete for the highest score in that game. In Multiplayer only attractions whoever wins wins. Each player who wins gets 3 points. Between rounds, players who aren't playing (if any) will vote on who they think will win and if they guess correctly they get two points. Whoever gets the most points after all the rounds wins the Attraction Tour.\n\n===Solo attractions===\nNumber of players: 1<ref name=\"n-styles1\"/>\n\n;''[[The Mysterious Murasame Castle|Takamaru's Ninja Castle]]''\nBased on the 1986 [[Famicom Disk System]] game ''[[The Mysterious Murasame Castle]]'', the player uses the [[Wii U GamePad|GamePad]]'s touchscreen to launch paper [[shuriken]] at waves of enemy ninjas. The controller can be tilted in order to change the trajectory of the throws. On boss ninjas or ninjas who are at close range, the players uses a katana.<ref name=verge-nl>{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land could be Wii U's system selling new game|url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/6/5/3064891/nintendo-land-could-be-wii-us-system-selling-new-game|website=The Verge|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n;''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong's Crash Course]]''\nThe player uses the GamePad's gyroscope abilities to tilt a trolley through a platform-based obstacle course, influenced by the [[Donkey Kong (video game)|original ''Donkey Kong'' arcade game]]. In addition to the tilt input to move the trolley, the player controls the GamePad's two analog sticks, L and R shoulder buttons, and microphone to activate various levers, elevators, and pathways to advance themselves throughout the course.\n\n;''[[F-Zero|Captain Falcon's Twister Race]]''\nA single-player game based on Nintendo's futuristic racing game ''[[F-Zero]]'', where the player must race down a track while avoiding obstacles in 12 different areas.<ref name=ign-fzero>{{cite web|title=E3 2012: The F-Zero Franchise Joins the Nintendo Land Line-Up|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2012/06/06/e3-2012-the-f-zero-franchise-joins-the-nintendo-land-line-up|website=IGN|accessdate=6 June 2012}}</ref> The GamePad is held vertically and its internal gyroscope is used to steer the vehicle when the player rotates the GamePad. The GamePad provides an aerial view (a more strategical view) of the track while the TV provides a third-person view on the track.\n\n;''[[Balloon Fight|Balloon Trip Breeze]]''\nIn this single-player game, based on Nintendo's ''[[Balloon Fight]]'', the player will control their Mii on a play-field similar to the Balloon Trip mode. The player does this by swiping the stylus on the GamePad's touch screen to create gusts of wind that will move the Mii around. The GamePad will offer a zoomed-in view for more precise input whereas the TV will offer a zoomed-out view to see more of the level. The levels are divided into morning, afternoon, evening and night, which are all ended by landing on an island. Occasionally, there are packages on islands that the player can pick up to protect and deliver to the next island.\n\n;''[[List of Yoshi video games|Yoshi's Fruit Cart]]''\nThis attraction is based on the [[List of Yoshi video games|''Yoshi'']] series. The player uses the stylus on the GamePad touchscreen to draw a trail that guides Yoshi to the finish goal of each level while collecting all the fruit in the area. The fruit is only visible on the TV screen, so the player must use reference points in the level's background to draw the path on the GamePad. As the player advances in level, obstacles will appear that take away a life from Yoshi if he is led into one.\n\n;''[[List of Game & Watch games|Octopus Dance]]''\nThis attraction is based on [[List of Game & Watch games|''Game & Watch Octopus'']]. ''Octopus Dance'' is a rhythm game which plays by using the GamePad's Control Sticks and Gyro Sensor. Players must memorize and replicate the actions performed by the instructor on screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/32152 |title=Final Nintendo Land Attractions Explained - News |publisher=Nintendo World Report |date=2012-10-17 |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nDevelopment started shortly after the release of [[Wii Sports Resort]] <ref name=\"Polygoninterview\">{{cite web |last1=Gifford |first1=Kevin |title=Nintendo Land: The postmortem interview |url=https://www.polygon.com/2012/12/12/3757884/nintendo-land-the-postmortem-interview |website=Polygon |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> and was made at a time when the Wii U hadn't been finalized yet which led to the team experimenting with different prototypes. One of said prototypes involved the use of a [[gyroscope]] which directly led to  [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] incorporating the technology into the [[Nintendo 3DS]].<ref name=\"Iwattaasks\">{{cite web |title=Development Started at the Same Time with Wii U |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wiiu/nintendo-land/0/0 |website=Ninteno}}</ref>\n\nThe teams goal was to create a product that showcased all the features the new console could do. This led to a problem, as unlike the similar [[Wii Sports]], the games were not inherently related. <ref name=\"Polygoninterview\"/> Early on one staff member suggested that they attempt to do something that would unite the various Nintendo  franchises. As the team considered this too grand a concept the idea was, at first not taken seriously. <ref name=\"Iwattaasks\"/> The developers initially decided to present the theme as an \"Expo\" which lead to the theme park concept. <ref name=\"Polygoninterview\"/> Although most attractions were easy to theme, the team struggled with some: ''Metroid Blast'' was initially themed around [[Star Fox]], while at one point it was considered to theme ''Donkey Kong Crash Course'' around either [[Excitebike|ExciteBike]] or [[1080\u00b0 Snowboarding|1080 Snowboarding.]] <ref name=\"Polygoninterview\"/>.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 78%<ref name=\"gamerankings\"/>\n| MC = 77/100<ref name=\"metacritic\"/>\n| 1UP = B+<ref name=\"1up review\"/>\n| Edge = 7/10<ref name=\"edge review\"/>\n| EuroG = 8/10<ref name=\"eurog review\"/>\n| GI = 7/10<ref name=\"gi review\"/>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"gamerev review\"/>\n| GSpot = 8/10<ref name=\"gspot review\"/>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"gradar review\"/>\n| IGN = 8.7/10<ref name=\"ign review\"/>\n| NLife = 9/10<ref name=\"nlife review\"/>\n| NWR = 8.5/10<ref name=\"nwr review\"/>\n| ONM = 90%<ref name=\"onm review\"/>\n| Poly = 8/10<ref name=\"poly review\"/>\n}}\n\nThe game has received positive reviews from video games critics, praising its party atmosphere and attractions, especially the way they are developed and built up, with a few being critical of simply showing Wii U GamePad capabilities. [[IGN]] praised the game for showing the Wii U capabilities, its gameplay, its detailed and HD graphics and claiming that \"Wii Sports has met its match\", giving it an 8.7 score.<ref name=\"ign review\"/>\n\n=== Sales ===\nBy March 2014, the game had sold 3.09 million copies,<ref name =\"march 2013 sales\"/> and by December 2014, it had sold 4.44 million units worldwide.<ref name =\"december 2014 sales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2015/150129e.pdf|title=Nintendo Earning Release Dec. 2014|publisher=Nintendo|date=2015-01-29|accessdate=2015-01-29}}</ref> {{As of|2018|9|30|df=US}}, the game has sold 5.19 million copies.<ref name=\"nincojp\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"1up review\">{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land Review: Good Fun, But What Does It Mean?|website=[[1UP.com]]|url=http://www.1up.com/reviews/nintendo-land-review-good-fun|accessdate=December 21, 2013|author=Parish, Jeremy|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123130824/http://www.1up.com/reviews/nintendo-land-review-good-fun|archivedate=January 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"edge review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.edge-online.com/review/nintendo-land-review/ |title=Nintendo Land review |date=November 16, 2012 |magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"eurog review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-15-nintendo-land-review |website=[[Eurogamer]] |author=Welsh, Oil |title=Nintendo Land Review |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |date=November 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gamerankings\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamerankings.com/wii-u/673043-nintendo-land/index.html |title=Nintendo Land for Wii U |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |publisher=[[GameRankings]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"gamerev review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesradar.com/nintendo-land-review/ |title=Nintendo Land Review |date=November 20, 2012 |author=Severino, Anthony |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |publisher=[[Game Revolution]]}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=\"gametrailers review\">{{cite web|title=Nintendo Land Review|publisher=[[GameTrailers]]|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/9dh9tl/nintendo-land-review |accessdate=December 21, 2013 |date=November 18, 2012}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"gi review\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/nintendo_land/b/wii_u/archive/2012/11/15/nintendo-land-review.aspx |title=Nintendo Land review |author=Wallace, Kimberley |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |