alls to the Wall\n|{{dts|2006|May|20}}\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|0:35\n|[[Helsinki]], Finland\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|1\u20130\n|Sergey Denisov\n|Submission (rear naked choke)\n|EKH - MMA Action\n|{{dts|2006|January|14}}\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1:48\n|[[Espoo]], Finland\n|\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://twitter.com/Anton_Kuivanen Twitter]\n* [http://www.mixedmartialarts.fi/anton-kuivasen-haastattelu-21-8-2012/ Anton Kuivasen haastattelu 21.8.2012]\n* {{Sherdog}}\n* {{UFC|Anton-Kuivanen}}\n* [http://www.antonkuivanen.fi Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kuivanen, Anton}}\n[[Category:Finnish male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Lightweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Finnish practitioners of Brazilian jiu-jitsu]]\n[[Category:Finnish capoeira practitioners]]\n[[Category:Finnish Muay Thai practitioners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Estonian emigrants to Finland]]\n[[Category:Finnish people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:Finnish people of Estonian descent]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriates in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship male fighters]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUltimate Fighting Championship:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1-2 \u2192 1\u20132", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anton_Kuivanen"}
{"title_page": "1862 in Germany", "text_new": "{{short description|Events from the year 1862 in Germany}}\n{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}\n{{Year in Germany|1862}}\nEvents from the year '''1862 in [[Germany]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n* [[King of Bavaria]] \u2013 [[Maximilian II of Bavaria]]\n* [[King of Saxony]] \u2013 [[John of Saxony|John]]\n* [[King of Hanover]] \u2013 [[George V of Hanover|George V]]<ref>Weir, Alison (18 April 2011). \"The House of Hanover\". Britain's Royal Families: The Complete Genealogy. Random House. p. 291.</ref>\n* [[List of rulers of Prussia|King of Prussia]] \u2013 [[William I, German Emperor|William I]]\n* [[King of W\u00fcrttemberg]] \u2013 [[William I of W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n* [[Grand Duke of Baden]] \u2013 [[Frederick I, Grand Duke of Baden|Frederick I]]\n\n==Events==\n* [[9 August]] \u2013 [[Theater Baden-Baden]] opens with [[B\u00e9atrice et B\u00e9n\u00e9dict]].\n* [[21 September]] \u2013 ''Deutscher S\u00e4ngerbund'' is founded.\n* [[30 September]] \u2013 [[Otto von Bismarck]] gives the speech named ''[[Blood and Iron (speech)|Blood and Iron]]'' in Berlin.\n\n===Undated===\n*[[Landesmuseum W\u00fcrttemberg]] is opened.\n\n==Births==\n* [[1 January]] \u2013 [[Heinrich Braun]], German surgeon (died [[1934 in Germany|1934]])\n* [[6 January]] \u2013 [[August Oetker]], German businessman (died [[1918 in Germany|1918]])\n* [[9 January]] \u2013 [[Agnes Bluhm]], German physician (died [[1943 in Germany|1943]])\n* [[20 January]] \u2013 [[Karl von Tubeuf]], German forestry scientist, mycologist and plant pathologist (died [[1941 in Germany|1941]])\n* [[23 January]] \u2013 [[David Hilbert]], German mathematician (died [[1943 in Germany|1943]])\n* [[24 January]] \u2013 [[Prince Alfons of Bavaria]], German nobleman (died [[1933 in Germany|1933]])\n* [[6 February]] \u2013 [[Joseph Friedrich Nicolaus Bornm\u00fcller]], German botanist (died [[1946 in Germany|1946]])\n* [[22 February]] \u2013 [[Philipp von Hellingrath]], German general (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[13 March]] \u2013 [[Wilhelm Weigand]], German poet and writer (died [[1949 in Germany|1949]])\n* [[11 April]] \u2013 [[Heinrich Cunow]], German politician (died [[1936 in Germany|1936]])\n* [[28 May]] \u2013 [[Theodor Fischer]], German architect (died [[1938 in Germany|1938]])\n* [[7 June]] \u2013 [[Philipp Lenard]], German physicist and the winner of the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1905 (died [[1947 in Germany|1947]])\n* [[12 June]] \u2013 [[Wilhelm Meyer-F\u00f6rster]], German novelist (died [[1934 in Germany|1934]])\n* [[18 June]] \u2013 [[Otto Immisch]], German philologist (died [[1936 in Germany|1936]])\n* [[12 August]] \u2013 [[Martin Brendel]], German astronomer (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[14 August]] \u2013 [[Prince Henry of Prussia (1862\u20131929)|Prince Henry of Prussia]], German Prussian prince (died [[1929 in Germany|1929]])\n* [[16 August]] \u2013 [[Ludwig Hermann Plate]], German zoologist (died [[1937 in Germany|1937]])\n* [[20 August]] \u2013 [[Paul St\u00e4ckel]], German mathematician (died [[1919 in Germany|1919]])\n* [[26 August]] \u2013 [[Theodor Siebs]], German linguist (died [[1941 in Germany|1941]])\n* [[11 September]] \u2013 [[Augustin Henninghaus]], German Roman Catholic missionary (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[15 September]] \u2013 [[Friedrich von Lindequist]], German gouverneur of German South#West Africa (died [[1945 in Germany|1945]])\n* [[2 October]] \u2013 [[Karl Ebermaier]], German governeur of Kamerun (died [[1943 in Germany|1943]])\n* [[4 October]] \u2013 [[Sebastian Finsterwalder]], German mathematician (died [[1951 in Germany|1951]])\n* [[15 October]] \u2013 [[Conrad Ansorge]], German composer and pianist (died [[1930 in Germany|1930]])\n* [[14 November]] \u2013 [[Johann Heinrich von Bernstorff]], German diplomat and ambassador (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[15 November]] \u2013 [[Gerhart Hauptmann]], German writer, Nobel Prize laureate (died [[1946 in Germany|1946]])\n* [[29 November]] \u2013 [[Friedrich Klose]], German composer (died [[1942 in Germany|1942]])\n* [[14 December]] \u2013 [[Gunther von Etzel]], German general (died [[1948 in Germany|1948]])\n\n==Deaths==\n* [[2 February]] \u2013 [[Rudolph Suhrlandt]], German painter (born [[1781 in Germany|1781]])\n* [[15 February]] \u2013 [[Heinrich Adam]], German painter (born [[1787 in Germany|1787]])\n* [[3 March]] \u2013 [[Princess Augusta Reuss of K\u00f6stritz]], German Grand Duchess of Mecklenburg-Schwerin (born [[1822 in Germany|1822]])\n* [[19 March]] \u2013 [[Friedrich Wilhelm Schadow]], German painter (born [[1789 in Germany|1789]])\n* [[15 July]] \u2013 [[Henriette Hanke]], German writer (born [[1785 in Germany|1785]])\n* [[28 August]] \u2013 [[Albrecht Adam]], German painter (born [[1786 in Germany|1786]])\n* [[12 November]] \u2013 [[Christian Gottlob Barth]], German theologian (born [[1799 in Germany|1799]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Year in Europe|1862}}\n\n[[Category:1862 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in Germany]]\n[[Category:1862 by country]]\n[[Category:1862 in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Events from the year 1862 in Germany}}\n{{refimprove|date=November 2018}}\n{{Year in Germany|1862}}\nEvents from the year '''1862 in [[Germany]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n* [[King of Bavaria]] \u2013 [[Maximilian II of Bavaria]]\n* [[King of Saxony]] \u2013 [[John of Saxony|John]]\n* [[King of Hanover]] \u2013 [[George V of Hanover|George V]]<ref>Weir, Alison (18 April 2011). \"The House of Hanover\". Britain's Royal Families: The Complete Genealogy. Random House. p. 291.</ref>\n* [[List of rulers of Prussia|King of Prussia]] \u2013 [[William I, German Emperor|William I]]\n* [[King of W\u00fcrttemberg]] \u2013 [[William I of W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n* [[Grand Duke of Baden]] \u2013 [[Frederick I, Grand Duke of Baden|Frederick I]]\n\n==Events==\n* [[9 August]] \u2013 [[Theater Baden-Baden]] opens with [[B\u00e9atrice et B\u00e9n\u00e9dict]].\n* [[21 September]] \u2013 ''Deutscher S\u00e4ngerbund'' is founded.\n* [[30 September]] \u2013 [[Otto von Bismarck]] gives the speech named ''[[Blood and Iron (speech)|Blood and Iron]]'' in Berlin.\n\n===Undated===\n*[[Landesmuseum W\u00fcrttemberg]] is opened.\n\n==Births==\n* [[1 January]] \u2013 [[Heinrich Braun]], German surgeon (died [[1934 in Germany|1934]])\n* [[6 January]] \u2013 [[August Oetker]], German businessman (died [[1918 in Germany|1918]])\n* [[9 January]] \u2013 [[Agnes Bluhm]], German physician (died [[1943 in Germany|1943]])\n* [[20 January]] \u2013 [[Karl von Tubeuf]], German forestry scientist, mycologist and plant pathologist (died [[1941 in Germany|1941]])\n* [[23 January]] \u2013 [[David Hilbert]], German mathematician (died [[1943 in Germany|1943]])\n* [[24 January]] \u2013 [[Prince Alfons of Bavaria]], German nobleman (died [[1933 in Germany|1933]])\n* [[6 February]] \u2013 [[Joseph Friedrich Nicolaus Bornm\u00fcller]], German botanist (died [[1946 in Germany|1946]])\n* [[22 February]] \u2013 [[Philipp von Hellingrath]], German general (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[13 March]] \u2013 [[Wilhelm Weigand]], German poet and writer (died [[1949 in Germany|1949]])\n* [[11 April]] \u2013 [[Heinrich Cunow]], German politician (died [[1936 in Germany|1936]])\n* [[28 May]] \u2013 [[Theodor Fischer]], German architect (died [[1938 in Germany|1938]])\n* [[7 June]] \u2013 [[Philipp Lenard]], German physicist and the winner of the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1905 (died [[1947 in Germany|1947]])\n* [[12 June]] \u2013 [[Wilhelm Meyer-F\u00f6rster]], German novelist (died [[1934 in Germany|1934]])\n* [[18 June]] \u2013 [[Otto Immisch]], German philologist (died [[1936 in Germany|1936]])\n* [[12 August]] \u2013 [[Martin Brendel]], German astronomer (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[14 August]] \u2013 [[Prince Henry of Prussia (1862\u20131929)|Prince Henry of Prussia]], German Prussian prince (died [[1929 in Germany|1929]])\n* [[16 August]] \u2013 [[Ludwig Hermann Plate]], German zoologist (died [[1937 in Germany|1937]])\n* [[20 August]] \u2013 [[Paul St\u00e4ckel]], German mathematician (died [[1919 in Germany|1919]])\n* [[26 August]] \u2013 [[Theodor Siebs]], German linguist (died [[1941 in Germany|1941]])\n* [[11 September]] \u2013 [[Augustin Henninghaus]], German roman-catholic missionary (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[15 September]] \u2013 [[Friedrich von Lindequist]], German gouverneur of German South#West Africa (died [[1945 in Germany|1945]])\n* [[2 October]] \u2013 [[Karl Ebermaier]], German governeur of Kamerun (died [[1943 in Germany|1943]])\n* [[4 October]] \u2013 [[Sebastian Finsterwalder]], German mathematician (died [[1951 in Germany|1951]])\n* [[15 October]] \u2013 [[Conrad Ansorge]], German composer and pianist (died [[1930 in Germany|1930]])\n* [[14 November]] \u2013 [[Johann Heinrich von Bernstorff]], German diplomat and ambassador (died [[1939 in Germany|1939]])\n* [[15 November]] \u2013 [[Gerhart Hauptmann]], German writer, Nobel Prize laureate (died [[1946 in Germany|1946]])\n* [[29 November]] \u2013 [[Friedrich Klose]], German composer (died [[1942 in Germany|1942]])\n* [[14 December]] \u2013 [[Gunther von Etzel]], German general (died [[1948 in Germany|1948]])\n\n==Deaths==\n* [[2 February]] \u2013 [[Rudolph Suhrlandt]], German painter (born [[1781 in Germany|1781]])\n* [[15 February]] \u2013 [[Heinrich Adam]], German painter (born [[1787 in Germany|1787]])\n* [[3 March]] \u2013 [[Princess Augusta Reuss of K\u00f6stritz]], German Grand Duchess of Mecklenburg-Schwerin (born [[1822 in Germany|1822]])\n* [[19 March]] \u2013 [[Friedrich Wilhelm Schadow]], German painter (born [[1789 in Germany|1789]])\n* [[15 July]] \u2013 [[Henriette Hanke]], German writer (born [[1785 in Germany|1785]])\n* [[28 August]] \u2013 [[Albrecht Adam]], German painter (born [[1786 in Germany|1786]])\n* [[12 November]] \u2013 [[Christian Gottlob Barth]], German theologian (born [[1799 in Germany|1799]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Year in Europe|1862}}\n\n[[Category:1862 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in Germany]]\n[[Category:1862 by country]]\n[[Category:1862 in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBirths:Typo fixing,typo(s) fixed: roman-catholic \u2192 Roman Catholic", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1862_in_Germany"}
{"title_page": "Fatima al-Batayahiyyah", "text_new": "{{notability|date=February 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Fatima al-Batayahiyyah\n| native_name        = \u0641\u0627\u0637\u0645\u06c1 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0637\u064a\u062d\u064a\u06c1\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| occupation         = Islamic Scholar\n| known_for          = \n| nationality        = \n| image              = Fatima al-Batayahiyyah.png\n| caption            = \n}}\n\n'''F\u0101\u021bima bint Ibrahim ibn Mahm\u016bd al-Ba\u021b\u0101'ihiyya''' also known as '''Fatima al-Batayahiyyah''' was a [[Muslim]] [[scholar]] of [[hadith]] in the 8th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last1=Aliyah|first1=Zainab|title=Great Women in Islamic History: A Forgotten Legacy|url=http://www.youngmuslimdigest.com/study/02/2015/great-women-islamic-history-forgotten-legacy/|website=Young Muslim Digest|accessdate=18 February 2015|date=2015-02-02}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n==Biography==\nFatima al-Batayahiyyah taught [[Sahih Bukhari]] in [[Damascus]]. She was known as one of the greatest scholars of that period, demonstrated especially during the [[Hajj]] when leading male scholars of the day flocked from afar to hear her speak in person.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|last1=Qazi|first1=Moin|title=Women In Islam- Exploring New Paradigms|date=2015|publisher=Notion Press|isbn=978-9384878030}}<!--|accessdate=27 February 2015--></ref>\n\nWhen she had become old, she moved to [[Madinah]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nadwi|first1=Mohammad Akram|title=Al Muhaddithat: the women scholars in Islam|date=2007|publisher=Interface Publishers|location=London|page=264}}</ref>  and taught her students for days in the [[Al-Masjid al-Nabawi|Prophet's mosque]] itself. Whenever she tired, she would rest her head on the [[Muhammad|Muhammad's]] grave and continue to teach her students.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Suleman and|first1=Mehrunisha|last2=Rajbee|first2=Afaaf|title=The Lost Female Scholars of Islam|url=http://www.emel.com/article?id&a_id=828|website=Emel magazine|publisher=Emel magazine|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref> This tradition is contrasted with the practice today, where people are not allowed view [[Muhammad|Muhammad's]] resting place.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muslim Scholars}}\n[[Category:8th-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n\n\n{{islam-book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=February 2015}}\n\n'''F\u0101\u021bima bint Ibrahim ibn Mahm\u016bd al-Ba\u021b\u0101'ihiyya''' also known as '''Fatima al-Batayahiyyah''' was a [[Muslim]] [[scholar]] of [[hadith]] in the 8th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last1=Aliyah|first1=Zainab|title=Great Women in Islamic History: A Forgotten Legacy|url=http://www.youngmuslimdigest.com/study/02/2015/great-women-islamic-history-forgotten-legacy/|website=Young Muslim Digest|accessdate=18 February 2015|date=2015-02-02}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n==Biography==\nFatima al-Batayahiyyah taught [[Sahih Bukhari]] in [[Damascus]]. She was known as one of the greatest scholars of that period, demonstrated especially during the [[Hajj]] when leading male scholars of the day flocked from afar to hear her speak in person.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|last1=Qazi|first1=Moin|title=Women In Islam- Exploring New Paradigms|date=2015|publisher=Notion Press|isbn=978-9384878030}}<!--|accessdate=27 February 2015--></ref>\n\nWhen she had become old, she moved to [[Madinah]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nadwi|first1=Mohammad Akram|title=Al Muhaddithat: the women scholars in Islam|date=2007|publisher=Interface Publishers|location=London|page=264}}</ref>  and taught her students for days in the [[Al-Masjid al-Nabawi|Prophet's mosque]] itself. Whenever she tired, she would rest her head on the [[Muhammad|Muhammad's]] grave and continue to teach her students.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Suleman and|first1=Mehrunisha|last2=Rajbee|first2=Afaaf|title=The Lost Female Scholars of Islam|url=http://www.emel.com/article?id&a_id=828|website=Emel magazine|publisher=Emel magazine|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref> This tradition is contrasted with the practice today, where people are not allowed view [[Muhammad|Muhammad's]] resting place.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muslim Scholars}}\n[[Category:8th-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n\n\n{{islam-book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "\u067e\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0632 \u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated photo.  Islamic calligraphy name.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatima_al-Batayahiyyah"}
{"title_page": "Nilla Fischer", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Nilla Fischer\n| image       = Nilla Fischer (cropped).jpg\n| caption     = Nilla Fischer in 2013\n| fullname    = \u00c5sa Nilla Maria Fischer<ref>{{cite web|title=Nilla Fischer\n|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fi/nilla-fischer-1.html|publisher=Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=9 June 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|8|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf |title= List of Players \u2013 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Kristianstad]], [[Sweden]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/damer/spelarportratt/?profile=27314 |title= Profile |language=Swedish |work=[[Swedish Football Association|Svenska Fotbollf\u00f6rbundet]] |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n| height      = {{height|m=1.75|precision=0}}<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\"/>\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]] / [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Link\u00f6pings FC]]\n| clubnumber  = 5\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = Verums GoIF\n| years1      = 1998\u20132000\n| years2      = 2000\u20132003\n| years3      = 2003\u20132011\n| years4      = 2012\u20132013\n| years5      = 2013\u20132019\n| years6      = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1      = [[Vittsj\u00f6 GIK]]\n| clubs2      = [[Kristianstads DFF|Kristianstad/W\u00e4 DFF]]\n| clubs3      = [[FC Roseng\u00e5rd|LdB FC Malm\u00f6]]\n| clubs4      = [[Link\u00f6pings FC]]\n| clubs5      = [[VfL Wolfsburg (women)|VfL Wolfsburg]]\n| clubs6      = [[Linkopings FC]]\n| caps1       = \n| caps2       = \n| caps3       = 136\n| caps4       = 33\n| caps5       = 125\n| caps6       = 5\n| goals1      = 0\n| goals2      = 0\n| goals3      = 24\n| goals4      = 2\n| goals5      = 11\n| goals6      = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132001\n| nationalteam1  = [[Sweden women's national under-17 football team|Sweden U17]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 12<ref name=\"nilla\">[https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/landslagsdatabas/landslagsspelare/?fplid=190086&tab=stats Caps and goals]</ref>\n| nationalgoals1 = 3<ref name=\"nilla\"/>\n| nationalyears2 = 2001\u20132004\n| nationalteam2  = [[Sweden women's national under-19 football team|Sweden U20]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 24<ref name=\"nilla\">[https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/landslagsdatabas/landslagsspelare/?fplid=190086&tab=stats Caps and goals]</ref>\n| nationalgoals2 = 4<ref name=\"nilla\"/>\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u2013\n| nationalteam3  = [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 182<ref name=\"nilla\">[https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/landslagsdatabas/landslagsspelare/?fplid=190086&tab=stats Caps and goals]</ref>\n| nationalgoals3 = 23<ref name=\"nilla\"/>\n| pcupdate = 22 April 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 6 July 2019\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|soccer]]}}\n{{Medal|Country| {{SWE}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[FIFA Women's World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|2011 Germany]]|Team}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019 France]]|Team}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''\u00c5sa Nilla Maria Fischer''' (born 2 August 1984) is a Swedish [[Association football|footballer]] for [[Link\u00f6pings FC]] and the [[Sweden women's national football team|Swedish national team]].<ref>[https://svenskfotboll.se/arkiv/damallsvenskan/2011/10/nilla-fischer-till-linkoping/ Nilla Fischer till Link\u00f6ping] Svenskfotboll.se</ref> She was previously the [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of [[FC Roseng\u00e5rd|LdB FC Malm\u00f6]].\n\n==Career==\nFischer won most of her [[Cap (sports)|caps]] for Sweden as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] after her debut versus [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]] in January 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fischer, Nilla|url=https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/damer/tidigare-ar/spelaret-2008/spelarportratt-2008/?profile=22041|publisher=[[Swedish Football Association]]|accessdate=4 August 2013|language=Swedish}}</ref> Approaching a century of appearances, she was converted to a [[centre back]] by coach [[Pia Sundhage]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confident Fischer's case for Sweden's defence|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenseuro/news/newsid=1949661.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=21 May 2013|first=Jo|last=Juvet}}</ref>\n\nThe change in position coincided with an upturn in goalscoring form for Fischer, who scored three times for hosts Sweden at [[UEFA Women's Euro 2013]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fischer enjoys her goalscoring glory|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenseuro/news/newsid=1971312.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=15 July 2013|first=Robert |last= Johansson}}</ref> Her performances in Sweden's run to the semi-finals prompted a contract offer from European Champions [[VfL Wolfsburg (women)|VfL Wolfsburg]] and Fischer agreed to move to Germany from 1 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wolfsburg seal deal for Sweden defender Fischer|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=1977968.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=30 July 2013}}</ref> In August 2013 the clubs reached a deal for \"grateful\" Fischer's immediate transfer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fischer completes Wolfsburg move|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=1981018.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=14 August 2013|date=14 August 2013}}</ref> Fischer played the first competitive game for her new side in the [[2013\u201314 Bundesliga (women)|Bundesliga 2013\u201314]] season opener against [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern Munich]] in front of a home crowd of 8,249 fans on 7 September 2013.\n\n==Matches and goals scored at World Cup & Olympic tournaments==\nNilla Fischer has represented Sweden in four [[FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cups]] ([[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|China 2007]], [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|Germany 2011]], [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|Canada 2015]], [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|France 2019]]) and three [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] ([[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing 2008]], [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]], [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Rio 2016]].) Her squad finished in third place in two of those World Cups (2011 and 2019), and won a Silver Medal in Rio.\n\nTwice during Olympic play she scored her team's only goal of the match, securing wins against [[Argentina women's national football team|Argentina]] in 2008 and [[South Africa women's national football team|South Africa]] in 2016.\n\nHer 35th minute goal against the [[United States women's national soccer team|USA]] on the final day of group play in the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group C|2011 World Cup]] would prove to be the match winner. That result put Sweden atop their group, and is the only time the Americans have suffered defeat in the group stage of a World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lauletta|first1=Dan|title=A brief history of the USWNT\u2019s group opponents: Sweden (who else?) and two relative newbies|url=https://equalizersoccer.com/2018/12/08/uswnt-history-2019-womens-world-cup-sweden-thailand-chile/|accessdate=14 December 2019|publisher=The Equalizer|date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{football international goals keys|olympic world cup final=y}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"fontsize:90%;\"\n|-\n! Goal\n! Match\n! Date\n! Location\n! Opponent\n! Lineup\n! Min\n! Score\n! Result\n! Competition\n|-\n| colspan=10 align=center {{fb bg world cup final tournament}} | {{flagicon|CHN}} '''[[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|China 20