ory:Footballers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sweden women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:2011 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Kristianstads DFF players]]\n[[Category:Damallsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Link\u00f6pings FC players]]\n[[Category:FC Roseng\u00e5rd players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from Sweden]]\n[[Category:Lesbian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:LGBT association football players]]\n[[Category:VfL Wolfsburg (women) players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Women's association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Sweden]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in football]]\n[[Category:2019 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2007 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Nilla Fischer\n| image       = Nilla Fischer (cropped).jpg\n| caption     = Nilla Fischer in 2013\n| fullname    = \u00c5sa Nilla Maria Fischer<ref>{{cite web|title=Nilla Fischer\n|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fi/nilla-fischer-1.html|publisher=Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=9 June 2013}}</ref>\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|8|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\">{{cite news |url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf |title= List of Players \u2013 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Kristianstad]], [[Sweden]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/damer/spelarportratt/?profile=27314 |title= Profile |language=Swedish |work=[[Swedish Football Association|Svenska Fotbollf\u00f6rbundet]] |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n| height      = {{height|m=1.75|precision=0}}<ref name=\"FIFA 2015\"/>\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]] / [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Link\u00f6pings FC]]\n| clubnumber  = 5\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = Verums GoIF\n| years1      = 1998\u20132000\n| years2      = 2000\u20132003\n| years3      = 2003\u20132011\n| years4      = 2012\u20132013\n| years5      = 2013\u20132019\n| years6      = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1      = [[Vittsj\u00f6 GIK]]\n| clubs2      = [[Kristianstads DFF|Kristianstad/W\u00e4 DFF]]\n| clubs3      = [[FC Roseng\u00e5rd|LdB FC Malm\u00f6]]\n| clubs4      = [[Link\u00f6pings FC]]\n| clubs5      = [[VfL Wolfsburg (women)|VfL Wolfsburg]]\n| clubs6      = [[Linkopings FC]]\n| caps1       = \n| caps2       = \n| caps3       = 136\n| caps4       = 33\n| caps5       = 125\n| caps6       = 5\n| goals1      = 0\n| goals2      = 0\n| goals3      = 24\n| goals4      = 2\n| goals5      = 11\n| goals6      = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132001\n| nationalteam1  = [[Sweden women's national under-17 football team|Sweden U17]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 12<ref name=\"nilla\">[https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/landslagsdatabas/landslagsspelare/?fplid=190086&tab=stats Caps and goals]</ref>\n| nationalgoals1 = 3<ref name=\"nilla\"/>\n| nationalyears2 = 2001\u20132004\n| nationalteam2  = [[Sweden women's national under-19 football team|Sweden U20]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 24<ref name=\"nilla\">[https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/landslagsdatabas/landslagsspelare/?fplid=190086&tab=stats Caps and goals]</ref>\n| nationalgoals2 = 4<ref name=\"nilla\"/>\n| nationalyears3 = 2001\u2013\n| nationalteam3  = [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 182<ref name=\"nilla\">[https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/landslagsdatabas/landslagsspelare/?fplid=190086&tab=stats Caps and goals]</ref>\n| nationalgoals3 = 23<ref name=\"nilla\"/>\n| pcupdate = 22 April 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 6 July 2019\n| medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|soccer]]}}\n{{Medal|Country| {{SWE}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[FIFA Women's World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|2011 Germany]]|Team}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019 France]]|Team}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|Team]]}}\n}}\n'''\u00c5sa Nilla Maria Fischer''' (born 2 August 1984) is a Swedish [[Association football|footballer]] for [[Link\u00f6pings FC]] and the [[Sweden women's national football team|Swedish national team]].<ref>[https://svenskfotboll.se/arkiv/damallsvenskan/2011/10/nilla-fischer-till-linkoping/ Nilla Fischer till Link\u00f6ping] Svenskfotboll.se</ref> She was previously the [[Captain (association football)|captain]] of [[FC Roseng\u00e5rd|LdB FC Malm\u00f6]].\n\n==Career==\nFischer won most of her [[Cap (sports)|caps]] for Sweden as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] after her debut versus [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]] in January 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fischer, Nilla|url=https://svenskfotboll.se/landslag/damer/tidigare-ar/spelaret-2008/spelarportratt-2008/?profile=22041|publisher=[[Swedish Football Association]]|accessdate=4 August 2013|language=Swedish}}</ref> Approaching a century of appearances, she was converted to a [[centre back]] by coach [[Pia Sundhage]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confident Fischer's case for Sweden's defence|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenseuro/news/newsid=1949661.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=9 June 2013|date=21 May 2013|first=Jo|last=Juvet}}</ref>\n\nThe change in position coincided with an upturn in goalscoring form for Fischer, who scored three times for hosts Sweden at [[UEFA Women's Euro 2013]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fischer enjoys her goalscoring glory|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenseuro/news/newsid=1971312.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=15 July 2013|first=Robert |last= Johansson}}</ref> Her performances in Sweden's run to the semi-finals prompted a contract offer from European Champions [[VfL Wolfsburg (women)|VfL Wolfsburg]] and Fischer agreed to move to Germany from 1 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wolfsburg seal deal for Sweden defender Fischer|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=1977968.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=4 August 2013|date=30 July 2013}}</ref> In August 2013 the clubs reached a deal for \"grateful\" Fischer's immediate transfer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fischer completes Wolfsburg move|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=1981018.html|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|accessdate=14 August 2013|date=14 August 2013}}</ref> Fischer played the first competitive game for her new side in the [[2013\u201314 Bundesliga (women)|Bundesliga 2013\u201314]] season opener against [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern Munich]] in front of a home crowd of 8,249 fans on 7 September 2013.\n\n==Matches and goals scored at World Cup & Olympic tournaments==\nNilla Fischer has represented Sweden in four [[FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cups]] ([[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|China 2007]], [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|Germany 2011]], [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|Canada 2015]], [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|France 2019]]) and three [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] ([[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Beijing 2008]], [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics|London 2012]], [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Rio 2016]].) Her squad finished in third place in two of those World Cups (2011 and 2019), and won a Silver Medal in Rio.\n\nTwice during Olympic play she scored her teams only goal of the match, securing wins against [[Argentina women's national football team|Argentina]] in 2008 and [[South Africa women's national football team|South Africa]] in 2016.\n\nHer 35th minute goal against the [[United States women's national soccer team|USA]] on the final day of group play in the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group C|2011 World Cup]] would prove to be the match winner. That result put Sweden atop their group, and is the only time the Americans have suffered defeat in the group stage of a World Cup.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lauletta|first1=Dan|title=A brief history of the USWNT\u2019s group opponents: Sweden (who else?) and two relative newbies|url=https://equalizersoccer.com/2018/12/08/uswnt-history-2019-womens-world-cup-sweden-thailand-chile/|accessdate=14 December 2019|publisher=The Equalizer|date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{football international goals keys|olympic world cup final=y}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"fontsize:90%;\"\n|-\n! Goal\n! Match\n! Date\n! Location\n! Opponent\n! Lineup\n! Min\n! Score\n! Result\n! Competition\n|-\n| colspan=10 align=center {{fb bg world cup final tournament}} | {{flagicon|CHN}} '''[[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|China 2007 FIFA Women's World Cup]]'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:white;\" |\n| <center>1</center>\n| 2007-9-14<ref group=m name=mat001>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/round=248549/match=56317/index.html#nosticky |title=FIFA Women's World Cup China 2007: MATCH Report: Sweden - USA: Group matches |publisher=FIFA}}</ref>\n| [[Chengdu]]\n| {{fbw|USA}}\n| {{subin|65|Therese|Sj\u00f6gran|s|Therese Sj\u00f6gran}}\n| style=\"background:white;\" |\n| style=\"background:white;\" |\n| {{sortfbs|0|2||||r}}\n| {{fb bg world cup final tournament}} | [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group B|Group match]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:white;\" |\n| <center>2</center>\n| 2007-9-18<ref group=m name=mat002>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/round=248549/match=56314/index.html#nosticky |title=FIFA Women's World Cup China 2007: MATCH Repor