/nyregion/pomp-and-humor-blend-as-yale-graduates-3013.html |title=Pomp And Humor Blend As Yale Graduates 3,013 |last=Freedman |first=Samuel G. |date=May 24, 1983 |website=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524142720/http://www.nytimes.com/1983/05/24/nyregion/pomp-and-humor-blend-as-yale-graduates-3013.html |archive-date=May 24, 2015 |access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Meryl Streep on screen and stage]]\n* [[List of actors with Academy Award nominations]]\n* [[List of actors with two or more Academy Awards in acting categories]]\n* [[List of actors with two or more Academy Award nominations in acting categories]]\n* [[List of stars on the Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n* [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars]]\n* [[List of Yale University people]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm0000658|Meryl Streep|section=awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Streep, Meryl}}\n[[Category:Meryl Streep]]\n[[Category:Lists of awards received by actor]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMiscellaneous Awards:more accurate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Meryl_Streep"}
{"title_page": "Vivianne Miedema", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Vivianne Miedema<br>{{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Orange-Nassau|RON]]}}\n| image = Vivianne Miedema beim Aufwaermen BL FCB gg. SGS Essen Muenchen-1 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| fullname = Anna Margaretha Marina Astrid Miedema<ref name=\"fifa\">{{cite web|title=List of Players \u2013 Netherlands|url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf|publisher=[[FIFA]]|accessdate=31 May 2015|page=16|format=PDF|date=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1996|07|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Hoogeveen]], Netherlands\n| height = {{height|cm=175}}<ref name=\"fifa\" />\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| clubnumber = 11\n| youthyears1 = 2001\u20132009\n| youthclubs1 = HZVV\n| youthyears2 = 2009\u20132011\n| youthclubs2 = VV de Weide\n| years1 = 2011\u20132014\n| caps1 = 69\n| goals1 = 78\n| clubs1 = [[SC Heerenveen (women)|SC Heerenveen]]\n| years2 = 2014\u20132017\n| caps2 = 61\n| goals2 = 35\n| clubs2 = [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern Munich]]\n| years3 = 2017\u2013\n| caps3 = 45\n| goals3 = 42\n| clubs3 = [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| nationalyears1 = 2010\u20132011\n| nationalteam1 = Netherlands U15\n| nationalcaps1 = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 10\n| nationalyears2 = 2010\u20132012\n| nationalteam2 = Netherlands U16\n| nationalcaps2 = 11\n| nationalgoals2 = 4\n| nationalyears3 = 2011\u20132012\n| nationalteam3 = Netherlands U17\n| nationalcaps3 = 11\n| nationalgoals3 = 22\n| nationalyears4 = 2013\n| nationalteam4 = Netherlands U19\n| nationalcaps4 = 10\n| nationalgoals4 = 7\n| nationalyears5 = 2013\u2013\n| nationalteam5 = [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 88\n| nationalgoals5 = 69\n| pcupdate = 30 January 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 10 March 2020 <ref name=ONS/>\n| medaltemplates      =\n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|the {{NED}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[FIFA Women's World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019 France]]|Team}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Women's Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[UEFA Women's Euro 2017|2017 Netherlands]]|Team}}\n}}\n'''Anna Margaretha Marina Astrid Miedema''' {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Orange-Nassau|RON]]}} ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0251na\u02d0 m\u0251r\u0263a\u02d0\u02c8re\u02d0ta\u02d0 ma\u02d0\u02c8rina\u02d0 \u02c8\u0294\u0251str\u026at \u02c8mid\u0259ma\u02d0}}; born 15 July 1996), commonly known as '''Vivianne Miedema''' ({{IPA-nl|vivi\u02c8j\u0251n\u0259|}}), is a Dutch [[Football player|professional footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for [[FA Women's Super League|FA WSL]] club [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[Netherlands women's national football team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.women.soccerway.com/players/vivianne-miedema/195616/|title=Netherlands \u2013 V. Miedema \u2013 Profile with news, career statistics and history \u2013 Women Soccerway|website=uk.women.soccerway.com|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> While at [[FC Bayern Munich (women)|Bayern Munich]] she won the [[Bundesliga (women)|Bundesliga]] twice. With Arsenal she won the [[2018\u201319 FA WSL|league title in 2019]]. With the Dutch national team she became [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017|European champion in 2017]]. She has scored more goals at international level for the Netherlands than any other player, across both the women\u2019s and men\u2019s teams.\n\n==Club career==\n[[File:Vivianne Miedema BL FCB gg. 1. FFC Frankfurt Muenchen-5.jpg|thumb|left|Vivianne Miedema with Bayern]]\nMiedema signed for [[SC Heerenveen (women)|SC Heerenveen]] at 14 and made her senior debut at 15, reportedly becoming the youngest ever player in the [[Eredivisie (women)|Eredivisie Vrouwen]].<ref name=sportschau>{{cite news|title=Vivianne Miedema: Der n\u00e4chste Superstar?|url=http://fifafrauenwm.sportschau.de/fifafrauenwm/nachrichten/Vivianne-Miedema-Der-naechste-Superstar-,miedema100.html|accessdate=14 June 2015|publisher=[[Sportschau]]|date=6 June 2015|language=German}}</ref> Her 39 goals for Heerenveen in the [[2013\u201314 BeNe League]] won her the top-scorer award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Star of 2014: Vivianne Miedema|url=http://www.uefa.com/womensunder19/news/newsid=2192611.html|publisher=[[UEFA]]|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiedema signed a contract with Bayern Munich in June 2014.<ref name=\"Summer2014/4transfers\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fcbayern-frauenfussball.de/news/FC+Bayern+verpflichtet+Vivianne+Miedema+und+Katie+Stengel,25762.htm |title=FC Bayern verpflichtet Vivianne Miedema und Katie Stengel |date=6 June 2014 |work=[[FC Bayern Munich (women)|FC Bayern Munich]] |accessdate=6 June 2014 |language=German}}</ref> In [[2014\u201315 Bundesliga (women)|poopoop\n2014\u201315]], she was part of a young Bayern team that remained unbeaten in the Bundesliga and won the title for the first time since 1976.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vivianne Miedema kampioen met Bayern M\u00fcnchen|url=http://www.nu.nl/voetbal/4046591/vivianne-miedema-kampioen-met-bayern-munchen.html|accessdate=14 June 2015|publisher=[[NU.nl]]|date=10 May 2015|language=Dutch}}</ref> She helped Bayern Munich defend the title the following season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kicker.de/frauen-bundesliga/spieltag/2015-16/22/0|publisher=Kicker}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Miedema went on to English club [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40018786|title=Vivianne Miedema: Bayern Munich striker joins Arsenal Ladies|website=BBC.com}}</ref> On 29 October, Vivianne scored her first goal in [[2017\u201318 FA WSL|England]] for Arsenal in the match with [[Everton L.F.C.|Everton]] on 23rd minute.\n\nMiedema scored a hat-trick as Arsenal defeated [[Liverpool F.C. Women|Liverpool]], 5\u20130, in the first match of the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45383041|title=WSL: Arsenal Women beat Liverpool Women 5\u20130 as Vivianne Miedema stars|date=2018-09-09|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-10-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> She brought her goals tally into double-digits with a brace against [[Bristol City W.F.C.|Bristol City]] in a 4\u20130 Arsenal victory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45930489|title=Women's Super League: Bristol City Women 0\u20134 Arsenal Women|date=2018-10-28|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-10-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> Miedema finished the season as the [[FA Women's Super League|WSL]] top scorer with 22 goals and was named [[PFA Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48065752|title=Virgil van Dijk and Vivianne Miedema win PFA Player of the Year awards|date=2019-04-28|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 October 2019, Miedema scored four goals in Arsenal's 5\u20132 victory against [[SK Slavia Praha (women)|Slavia Praha]] in the Women's Champion's League.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/oct/16/arsenals-vivianne-miedema-hits-four-in-champions-league-win-at-slavia-prague|title=Arsenal's Vivianne Miedema hits four in Champions League win at Slavia Prague|date=2019-10-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October 2019, Miedema was shortlisted for the [[Ballon d'Or F\u00e9minin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/oct/21/six-liverpool-players-on-ballon-dor-shortlist-bronze-and-white-nominated|title=Seven Liverpool players on Ballon d'Or shortlist, Bronze and White nominated|date=2019-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-22|agency=PA Media}}</ref>\n\nMiedema was influential in the [[Arsenal Women 11\u20131 Bristol City Women|largest victory in the history of the WSL]] on 1 December 2019 \u2014 of the 11 goals scored by Arsenal against Bristol City, she scored six goals and set up four others. The 11th was the only one she was not directly involved in; she wasn't on the pitch when it was scored.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50534277|title=Arsenal Women 11\u20131 Bristol City Women|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 December 2019|accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://amp.theguardian.com/football/2019/dec/04/vivianne-miedema-arsenal-six-goals-netherlands-forward Vivianne Miedema: Arsenal\u2019s six-goal headline stealer who hates limelight], The Guardian, <4 December 2019</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:20170716 WEURO NED NOR 3652.jpg|thumb|right|Vivianne Miedema during the European Championship]]\nOn 26 September 2013, [[Coach (sport)|coach]] [[Roger Reijners]] gave Miedema her debut for the senior [[Netherlands women's national football team]], in a 4\u20130 win against [[Albania women's national football team|Albania]].<ref name=ONS>{{cite web |title=Profile |url=https://www.onsoranje.nl/teams/207834/speler/3038 |language=Dutch |work=onsoranje.nl |accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> At the [[2014 UEFA Women's Under-19 Championship]], she was vital for the Dutch success, her six goals in the tournament guided the Netherlands to the title.<ref name=robben>{{cite web|title=Miedema: I play very differently to Robben|url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/y=2015/m=3/news=miedema-i-play-very-differently-to-robben-2556714.html|publisher=[[FIFA]]|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> She was the tournament top scorer by a margin of 4 goals and also collected the Golden Player awarded to the best player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/womensunder19/history/season=2014/goldenplayer/index.html|title=UEFA.com Golden Player 2014: Vivianne Miedema|publisher=UEFA.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Miedema played a key role in the Netherlands' World Cup qualification play-off victory over [[Scotland women's national football team|Scotland]]. In the first leg at [[Tynecastle Stadium]] she stung the palms of [[Gemma Fay]] with a rasping drive which was prodded home by [[Lieke Martens]]. Then she casually shrugged off burly centre-half [[Jennifer Beattie]] only to be crudely upended by [[Frankie Brown]] inside the box. [[Manon Melis]] dispatched the resultant penalty to leave the Dutch firmly in the driving seat ahead of the second leg in Rotterdam.<ref>{{cite news|title=Scotland 1\u20132 Netherlands: Little penalty gives Scots World Cup hope|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/international/297161-scotland-1-2-netherlands-little-penalty-gives-scots-world-cup-hope/|accessdate=5 June 2015|work=[[Scottish Television|STV]]|date=24 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the final qualification play-off versus [[Italy women's national football team|Italy]], Miedema scored all of the Dutch goals as the Netherlands won 3\u20132 on aggregate and advanced to the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref name=fifa/> She finished as the overall top-scorer in [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification|the qualification campaign]] with 16 goals.<ref name=robben /> Coach Reijners praised Miedema's \"killer instinct\".<ref name=sportschau /> Despite being still in her teens, she was widely proclaimed \"the most gifted striker in Europe\" ahead of the Netherlands' first ever [[FIFA Women's World Cup]] appearance.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Louise|title=Women\u2019s World Cup 2015: 10 players to watch|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2015/jun/05/womens-world-cup-2015-football-10-players-to-watch|accessdate=14 June 2015|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=5 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017|2017 UEFA Women's European Championship]] she went on to prove her worth when it mattered the most, scoring a winning goal in the semi-final against England. Miedema also netted two goals in the final against Denmark of which was enough to secure the first ever Euro title for the Dutch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/amp/news/miedema-fires-netherlands-to-euro-2017-title/1vnuc2rl4qtma13gdrv6nizyfo|title=Miedema fires Netherlands to Euro 2017 glory|website=Goal.com}}</ref> After the tournament the whole team was honoured by the [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands|Prime Minister]] [[Mark Rutte]] and [[Ministry of Health, Welfare and Sport|Minister of Sport]] [[Edith Schippers]] and made Knights of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2199703-voetbalsters-oranje-geridderd-in-den-haag.html|title=Voetbalsters Oranje geridderd in Den Haag (in Dutch)|website=NOS.nl}}</ref>\n\nMiedema was selected in the final squad for the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019 FIFA Women\u2019s World Cup]] in France.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.knvb.com/news/knvb/womens-football/903/sarina-wiegman-names-netherlands-women%E2%80%99s-world-cup-squad|title=Sarina Wiegman names Netherlands Women\u2019s World Cup squad|date=10 April 2019|publisher=[[Royal Dutch Football Association|KNVB]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2019, she became the all-time top scorer of the [[Netherlands women's national football team]] after scoring her 60th goal in a 3\u20131 win against Cameroon at the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/wk2019/artikel/2289197-recordhouder-miedema-na-dubbelslag-blij-dat-ik-dit-aan-het-team-kan-geven.html|title=Recordhouder Miedema na dubbelslag: 'Blij dat ik dit aan het team kan geven' (in Dutch)|website=NOS.nl}}</ref> She passed the record held by Manon Melis and moved even further ahead of the men's team leading scorer, Robin van Persie.<ref>{{cite news |last1=van Warmerdam |first1=Hidde |last2=Reedijk |first2=Tim |title=Miedema: Zonde dat Van Persie niet nog tien jaar voetbalt |url=https://www.ad.nl/wk-vrouwenvoetbal/miedema-zonde-dat-van-persie-niet-nog-tien-jaar-voetbalt~aae2bed7 |accessdate=30 June 2019 |publisher=[[Algemeen Dagblad]] |date=18 June 2019 |language=Dutch}}</ref> She scored both goals in the Netherlands' 2\u20130 quarter-final victory over [[Italy women's national football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/29/dutch-head-into-world-cup-semis-after-2-0-win-over-italy |title=Dutch head into World Cup semis after 2\u20130 win over Italy|work=Euronews |accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref> She helped to lead the Dutch team to the final, where they fell 2\u20130 to defending champions [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]].\n\n==Style of play==\nMiedema grew up as a [[Feyenoord]] supporter and modelled her game on [[Robin van Persie]]. As she is Dutch and wore number 10 for Bayern Munich, she has been compared to [[Arjen Robben]].<ref name=robben/> Journalist [[David Winner (author)|David Winner]], author of a book about Dutch football, sees her style of play as a mix of [[Marco van Basten]] and [[Dennis Bergkamp]].<ref>{[cite news|title=Oranje en Ajax worden weer bewonderd: 'Totaalvoetbal 5.0 of zoiets' |publisher=NOS|date= 31 December 2019|first=Jesse|last=Wieten|url=\nhttps://nos.nl/artikel/2316810-oranje-en-ajax-worden-weer-bewonderd-totaalvoetbal-5-0-of-zoiets.html}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMiedema lives 30 minutes north of London with her girlfriend, [[Scotland women's national football team|Scottish player]] and Arsenal teammate [[Lisa Evans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/gs-b117b227|title=Het leukste van Londen, getipt door Vivianne Miedema|last=Bosgraaf|first=Mirjam|date=2019-05-24|website=de Volkskrant|language=nl-NL|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=WePlayStrong|title=Check out this Arsenal football star's apartment! #WhySoSerious|date=2019-03-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zz8kiIXi3Io|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spelersvrouw.nl/lisa-evans-vriendin-vivianne-miedema/|title=Lisa Evans vriendin van Vivianne Miedema|date=2019-04-29|website=Spelersvrouw.nl|language=nl|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=roleofimagination|title=Vivianne Miedema \u2013 NOS Jeugdjournaal (English subtitles)|date=2019-06-02|url=https://vimeo.com/339873448|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://heavy.com/sports/2019/07/lisa-evans-vivianne-miedema-girlfriend/|title=Lisa Evans, Vivianne Miedema\u2019s Girlfriend: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Dodge|first=Sam|date=2019-07-07|website=Heavy.com|access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref>\n\nHer younger brother [[:nl:Lars Miedema|Lars]] is also a footballer, who as of 2020 was establishing himself in the first team at [[FC Den Bosch]].<ref name=Lars>[https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/artikel/4750466/wk-vrouwenvoetbal-frankrijk-vivianne-miedema-koprol-broer-lars-zus Lars Miedema over zus Vivianne: 'Scoren is gewoon haar job'] (Lars Miedema about sister Vivianne: 'Scoring is just her job'), [[RTL Nederland]] (in Dutch), 27 August 2019</ref> Known for her disinterest in overtly celebrating her many goals, she made an exception for the strike which made her the Dutch national top scorer in 2019 only as an agreement with her brother (who was in the stadium) who insisted she should mark the achievement.<ref name=Lars/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n[[File:Vivianne Miedema.jpg|thumb|right|Playing for Bayern Munich in 2015]]\n=== Club ===\n{{updated|29 February 2020| }}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width: 70%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=5%|Season\n!rowspan=2 width=20%|Club\n!rowspan=2 width=15%|Competition\n!colspan=2 width=12%|League\n!colspan=2 width=12%|Cups\n!colspan=2 width=12%|International Cups\n!colspan=2 width=12%|Total\n|-\n!width=6%|Games\n!width=6%|Goals\n!width=6%|Games\n!width=6%|Goals\n!width=6%|Games\n!width=6%|Goals\n!width=6%|Games\n!width=6%|Goals\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Eredivisie (women)|2011\u201312]]\n|rowspan=3|[[SC Heerenveen (women)|SC Heerenveen]]\n|rowspan=1|[[Eredivisie (women)|Eredivisie]]\n|17\n|10\n|2\n|2\n|colspan=2|\u2013\n|'''19'''\n|'''12'''\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 BeNe League|2012\u201313]]\n|rowspan=2|[[BeNe League]]\n|26\n|27\n|2\n|2\n|colspan=2|